questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The word &lt;strong&gt;surge&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;means a sudden large &lt;strong&gt;increase&lt;/strong&gt;, typically a temporary one. Hence&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;a&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;matches with&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;2.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The word&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;vigil&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;means a period of keeping awake during the time usually spent asleep, especially to keep &lt;strong&gt;watch&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;Hence &lt;b&gt;b&amp;nbsp;&lt;/b&gt;matches with &lt;b&gt;3.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The word&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;instance&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;means&amp;nbsp;an &lt;strong&gt;example &lt;/strong&gt;or single occurrence of something.&amp;nbsp;Hence &lt;strong&gt;c&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;matches with&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;1.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The only option that mentions all of these combinations is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;option 2.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let us look at the example:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Sachin Tendulkar is &lt;strong&gt;a great hand&lt;/strong&gt; at batting.&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;This idiom conveys the meaning&amp;nbsp;that he is very proficient at the activity of batting.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence,&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;option 1 is correct.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Company&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Solitude&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; means&amp;nbsp;the state or situation of being alone (एकांत).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Company&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; means the fact or condition of being with another or others, especially in a way that provides friendship and enjoyment (संगति).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence the correct antonym is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Company&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Option 1.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Individual&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; refers to a single human being as distinct from a group (व्यक्ति).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Ex&lt;/strong&gt;-&lt;strong&gt;serviceman&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; refers to a person who has served in the armed forces and is no longer serving (पूर्व सैनिक).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Victim&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; means a person harmed, injured, or killed as a result of a crime, accident, or other event or action (पीड़ित).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;2. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;lsquo;The best of both worlds&amp;rsquo; means to have advantages from to different things at the same time. &lt;strong&gt;&amp;lsquo;Come hell or high wate&lt;/strong&gt;r&amp;rsquo; means to face difficulties no matter what they are. To &amp;lsquo;break the ice&amp;rsquo; means to do something in order to relive the tension or get the conversation going. &amp;lsquo;By comparing apples to oranges&amp;rsquo; means to compare to very different things that are by their nature incomparable.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;2.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The idiom &lt;strong&gt;&amp;lsquo;have a bee in your bonnet&amp;rsquo;&lt;/strong&gt; is used to refer to a situation in which a person feels very strongly about a subject and keeps thinking or talking about it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, &lt;strong&gt;option 3&lt;/strong&gt; is correct.&lt;br /&gt;
Here are the meanings of the other idioms:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A bed of thorns &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;ndash; a situation full of difficulty&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A bird&amp;rsquo;s eye view&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; a view from a high angle&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Have a bone to pick&lt;/strong&gt; - to want to talk to someone about something annoying they have done&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Note:&amp;nbsp;(In the released official paper solutions, the answer has been incorrectly marked as&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;option 2&lt;/strong&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fusion&lt;/strong&gt; is a process of joining or combining two or more into one. &lt;strong&gt;Separation&lt;/strong&gt; is exactly the opposite process and is hence its antonym.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 2.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div data-dobid=&quot;dfn&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Disintegration &lt;/strong&gt;means the process of coming to pieces. Fusion and&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;combination&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;are synonyms.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div data-dobid=&quot;dfn&quot;&gt;
&lt;div data-dobid=&quot;dfn&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Distribution &lt;/strong&gt;is the process in which something is shared out among a group or spread over an area.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Option 2&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; i.e. &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Fly&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;word that means the same&lt;/strong&gt; as &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;soar&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;fly.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Soar&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is a verb that means to fly or rise high in the air, often rapidly and with ease.(&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;उड़ना)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It&amp;#39;s often used&lt;/strong&gt; to describe the flight of birds, airplanes, or other objects that can move through the air.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Fly&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is the correct answer, as it also means to move through the air, often with the help of wings.(&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;उड़ना)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It can be a verb (as in the act of flying) or a noun (as in the insect).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the &lt;strong&gt;correct answer&lt;/strong&gt; is:&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;Fly&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Now let&amp;#39;s look at the other words:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Sweet&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is an adjective that describes something with a pleasant taste that is similar to sugar.(मीठा)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Bitter&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;is an adjective used to describe a sharp, pungent taste that is often considered unpleasant. (कड़वा)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Sour&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;is an adjective that describes something with a taste like a lemon or vinegar, typically considered sharp or acidic.(खट्टा)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cut from the same cloth&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To be &amp;lsquo;slower than molasses&amp;rsquo; means to be extremely slow in something.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To be &amp;lsquo;throwing their weight around&amp;rsquo; means to use one&amp;rsquo;s position or status to get an unfair advantage over others.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To have &amp;lsquo;spare tires&amp;rsquo; means to have extra layers of fat around the waist.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To be&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;lsquo;cut from the same cloth&amp;rsquo;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;means to be of the same nature or to be similar. This fits the context of the sentence. Thus, the correct answer is option &lt;strong&gt;2.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The idiom &amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;keep in touch&amp;rsquo;&lt;/strong&gt; means &amp;lsquo;to maintain up-to-date knowledge about something&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given the context of the sentence, this idiom fits perfectly.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, &lt;strong&gt;option 4 is correct.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are the meanings of the other idioms:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;show your hand&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; to disclose your plans&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;put your foot in it&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; to say something without thinking carefully&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;stand your ground&lt;/strong&gt; - to refuse to change your opinion&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
